title: Plants Talk. Can We Understand?
description:
When plants are experiencing stress, they make noise. Can we understand what they're saying? Scientists at Tel Aviv University built soundproofed acoustic boxes with ultrasonic microphones - and used machine learning to understand what they heard. Like Dr. Doolittle, but for plants!

If you like optimistic science videos, you'll love this video that uncovers the truth about psychedelics: https://youtu.be/fpwDi8f6TLQ

term: Coral reefs heat-sink
title: Coral Reefs That Can Finally Beat the Heat | WILD HOPE
description:
Coral reefs around the world are threatened by rising ocean temperatures, but hope is growing off the coast of Hawaii. There, researchers at the Coral Resilience Lab selectively breed corals to withstand ever-increasing amounts of heat stress.

Corals are tiny animals that have a mutually beneficial relationship with an algae that lives within their cells. When stressed by heat, many expel their algae and turn white โ known as โbleachingโ โ losing their main source of food and often dying within days. Half of all coral has been lost since the 1950s. But some corals do survive these bleaching events, and theyโve become the focus of Kira Hughes and her teamโs work. By selectively breeding the coral that doesn't bleach, Kira hopes they can increase their resilience from one generation to the next.   

To scale up their efforts, Kiraโs team collects coral pieces that have naturally broken off in the ocean. With the help of volunteers, they prep and test these corals, and eventually replant the heat-tolerant corals theyโve found back into the reef they came from. This year, for the first time, the selectively bred coral โbabiesโ will be planted too, giving the reef a fighting chance to survive the warming ocean.

Learn more about this story and ways that YOU can get involved in saving your local biodiversity by becoming a Wild Hoper:

Scientists from the British Antarctic Survey are drilling ice cores in the Antarctic and analysing them to find out what the Earth's temperature and carbon dioxide levels were like in the past.

In this video, Ice Core Scientist Nerilie Abram reveals how we recover and study ice through the ages, and how this gives us an insight into how the Earth's climate is changing.

term: Ice core literature data library
title: Studying Ancient Ice {NICL} | Science Nation
description: It's a freezing cold day inside the National Ice Core Laboratory (NICL) in Denver, Colo., as it is every day of the year. That's because the NICL is a facility for storing and studying ice cores recovered from the polar regions of the world. It's minus 10 degrees Fahrenheit inside, so everyone is bundled up in ski parkas, insulated gloves and boots. And, saws are buzzing, as scientists from all over the U.S. are measuring and cutting pieces of precious Antarctic glacier ice to take back to their labs for research. While their research goals vary, all the scientists are here on this day for same thing - ice cores from the WAIS Divide Ice Core project. With support from the National Science Foundation (NSF), project manager Mark Twickler and a team of scientists, engineers, and support personnel traveled to the bottom of the world to drill and bring back these ice cores, which are perfectly preserved records of the distant past. The team drilled down more than two miles to retrieve the oldest pieces of ice in an ice sheet that's more than 70.000 years old. Twickler says ice core layers are like tree rings because each layer represents a year of weather. From the ice core layers, the scientists can learns all sort of information, from how rough the oceans were around Antarctica to how dusty it was in Australia.

pretty_text:
Title: Studying Ancient Ice {NICL} | Science Nation

Channel: National Science Foundation News

Description: It's a freezing cold day inside the National Ice Core Laboratory (NICL) in Denver, Colo., as it is every day of the year. That's because the NICL is a facility for storing and studying ice cores recovered from the polar regions of the world. It's minus 10 degrees Fahrenheit inside, so everyone is bundled up in ski parkas, insulated gloves and boots. And, saws are buzzing, as scientists from all over the U.S. are measuring and cutting pieces of precious Antarctic glacier ice to take back to their labs for research. While their research goals vary, all the scientists are here on this day for same thing - ice cores from the WAIS Divide Ice Core project. With support from the National Science Foundation (NSF), project manager Mark Twickler and a team of scientists, engineers, and support personnel traveled to the bottom of the world to drill and bring back these ice cores, which are perfectly preserved records of the distant past. The team drilled down more than two miles to retrieve the oldest pieces of ice in an ice sheet that's more than 70.000 years old. Twickler says ice core layers are like tree rings because each layer represents a year of weather. From the ice core layers, the scientists can learns all sort of information, from how rough the oceans were around Antarctica to how dusty it was in Australia.

title: Mutations (Updated)
description:
Join the Amoeba Sisters as they explain gene and chromosome mutations, and explore the significance of these changes. This updated video has improved audio and images! Check out our updated handout on https://www.amoebasisters.com/handouts and expand for table of contents!

Factual Reference:
OpenStax Biology 2nd Edition, Biology 2e. OpenStax CNX. May 8, 2019 http://cnx.org/contents/8d50a0af-948b-4204-a71d-4826cba765b8@15.43.

Codons and the amino acids they code for is represented by standard charts can be found in the public domain. While the rectangle chart is the common format, there may be other ways to represent the information. P.S. If exploring more about mutations, check out this cool codon chart that  includes mutations(!!) in the public domain: https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Notable_mutations.svg

***Further Reading Suggestions to Go Beyond This Content!***

Regarding "Random"
At the point where "random" is mentioned in the video, it is discussing the effect of whether the mutation is beneficial to the organism and we follow the sentence with, "The organism can't will itself to get a certain mutation." We chose to address this, because it's important to understand organisms are not "choosing a specific mutation to adapt and evolve." An additional, lengthier source from Berkeley explains "random" in regards to mutations is here: https://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/article/0_0_0/mutations_07   BUT keep in mind this is different than the mutation  rate or frequency which can be altered by both external and internal factors (we actually mention some at 1:38 ).  However, as we do think the word "random" could be interpreted as referring to different things, if we remake this video, we would prefer to spend some time on that discussion.  Several years after this video released, a fascinating study ( https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-021-04269-6 ) about a plant species and mutations was published and furthers this discussion about potential issues with the term "random." While the plants in the study are still not choosing specific mutations, the results indicated that these plants have mechanisms (such as epigenetic factors) that can reduce the occurrence of harmful mutations.

"Are Mutations Random?"
https://academic.oup.com/evolut/article/77/11/2522/7252632
 https://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/genetic-mutation-1127/

We think this conversation on Twitter/X started by one of the linked study's authors about the term "random" is an interesting read. https://x.com/Grey_Monroe/status/1481348377996447745

"Are Mutations Random?"
https://academic.oup.com/evolut/article/77/11/2522/7252632
 https://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/genetic-mutation-1127/

-Yes, mutations can happen in viruses! Check out master teacher John Mead's National Geographic Education blog post on this with the influenza virus: 
https://blog.education.nationalgeographic.org/2017/12/08/talking-evolution-the-challenge-of-influenza-part-2/

-Mutations in fruit flies? Learn more:
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4649653/
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4349060/

-Careers in Genetics?
National Society of Genetic Counselors: https://www.nsgc.org/page/aboutgeneticcounselors
Bioinformatics: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4408859/

text:
Mutations (Updated)Join the Amoeba Sisters as they explain gene and chromosome mutations, and explore the significance of these changes. This updated video has improved audio and images! Check out our updated handout on https://www.amoebasisters.com/handouts and expand for table of contents!

Factual Reference:
OpenStax Biology 2nd Edition, Biology 2e. OpenStax CNX. May 8, 2019 http://cnx.org/contents/8d50a0af-948b-4204-a71d-4826cba765b8@15.43.

Codons and the amino acids they code for is represented by standard charts can be found in the public domain. While the rectangle chart is the common format, there may be other ways to represent the information. P.S. If exploring more about mutations, check out this cool codon chart that  includes mutations(!!) in the public domain: https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Notable_mutations.svg

***Further Reading Suggestions to Go Beyond This Content!***

Regarding "Random"
At the point where "random" is mentioned in the video, it is discussing the effect of whether the mutation is beneficial to the organism and we follow the sentence with, "The organism can't will itself to get a certain mutation." We chose to address this, because it's important to understand organisms are not "choosing a specific mutation to adapt and evolve." An additional, lengthier source from Berkeley explains "random" in regards to mutations is here: https://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/article/0_0_0/mutations_07   BUT keep in mind this is different than the mutation  rate or frequency which can be altered by both external and internal factors (we actually mention some at 1:38 ).  However, as we do think the word "random" could be interpreted as referring to different things, if we remake this video, we would prefer to spend some time on that discussion.  Several years after this video released, a fascinating study ( https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-021-04269-6 ) about a plant species and mutations was published and furthers this discussion about potential issues with the term "random." While the plants in the study are still not choosing specific mutations, the results indicated that these plants have mechanisms (such as epigenetic factors) that can reduce the occurrence of harmful mutations.

"Are Mutations Random?"
https://academic.oup.com/evolut/article/77/11/2522/7252632
 https://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/genetic-mutation-1127/

We think this conversation on Twitter/X started by one of the linked study's authors about the term "random" is an interesting read. https://x.com/Grey_Monroe/status/1481348377996447745

"Are Mutations Random?"
https://academic.oup.com/evolut/article/77/11/2522/7252632
 https://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/genetic-mutation-1127/

-Yes, mutations can happen in viruses! Check out master teacher John Mead's National Geographic Education blog post on this with the influenza virus: 
https://blog.education.nationalgeographic.org/2017/12/08/talking-evolution-the-challenge-of-influenza-part-2/

-Mutations in fruit flies? Learn more:
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4649653/
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4349060/

term: fungi share knowledge
title: Fungi share genes
description:
In addition to inheritance, species can acquire genes through a process called horizontal gene transfer in which DNA is transferred between separate lineages. In this video abstract, Slot and Rokas explain their recent discovery that a large gene cluster encoding a biosynthesis pathway for an important toxin has transferred between two species of fungi. These findings highlight the potential importance of such clusters and horizontal gene transfer in the evolution of microbes, including important pathogens.

Check out the paper at http://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(10)01651-9.

And read more great research at http://www.cell.com/current-biology/home.

title: Climate change: understanding the facts (Vostok ice core)
description:
Original graph with scales for reference: https://images.newscientist.com/wp-content/uploads/2007/05/dn11640-1_800.jpg

In this whiteboard animation, I explain why global atmospheric temperature increases due to increased concentrations of carbon dioxide and methane. This is based on the Vostok ice core research published in 1999 and more recent research published by the European Project for Ice Coring in Antarctica (EPICA) and the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) report published in October 2013. title: Ice Memory : une bibliothรจque de glace pour les gรฉnรฉrations futures
description:
La glace nous parle. C'est elle qui nous aide ร comprendre le rรฉchauffement climatique qui nous menace. Elle nous raconte l'histoire de la Terre et pourrait mรชme nous aider ร nous protรฉger de futures pandรฉmies bactรฉriennes mondiales. Les glaciers sont des bibliothรจques dont la plupart des livres n'ont pas encore รฉtรฉ lus. Pour รฉviter que ces connaissances ne fondent avec la glace et ne soient dรฉfinitivement perdues, le projet Ice Memory tente de rรฉcolter des รฉchantillons, des carottes de glaces, pour les mettre en lieu sรปr. Une bibliothรจque de glace pour les millรฉnaires ร venir.

title: Mรฉcanismes de dรฉfense psychologique: L'impact cachรฉ sur notre comportement!
description:
Les mรฉcanismes de dรฉfense psychologique sont des stratรฉgies inconscientes que notre esprit utilise pour faire face ร des รฉmotions, des pensรฉes ou des situations stressantes ou menaรงantes. Ils nous aident ร rรฉduire l'anxiรฉtรฉ et ร protรฉger notre estime de soi. Cependant, ils peuvent รฉgalement avoir un impact cachรฉ sur notre comportement.

L'un des mรฉcanismes de dรฉfense les plus courants est la projection. Cela se produit lorsque nous attribuons nos propres pensรฉes, sentiments ou motivations inconscients ร quelqu'un d'autre. Par exemple, une personne qui a du mal ร accepter sa propre colรจre peut projeter cette colรจre sur les autres et les accuser d'รชtre en colรจre.

Un autre mรฉcanisme de dรฉfense est la rationalisation. Il s'agit de justifier ou d'expliquer nos comportements ou nos sentiments de maniรจre logique, mรชme si cela peut ne pas รชtre entiรจrement vrai. Par exemple, une personne qui รฉchoue ร un examen peut rationaliser en disant que l'examen รฉtait injuste ou que les questions รฉtaient trop difficiles, plutรดt que de reconnaรฎtre ses propres lacunes.

La rรฉpression est un mรฉcanisme de dรฉfense qui consiste ร refouler des pensรฉes, des souvenirs ou des รฉmotions inconfortables dans l'inconscient. Cela peut se produire lorsque nous essayons de bloquer ou d'oublier des expรฉriences traumatiques ou des dรฉsirs inacceptables. Cependant, ces pensรฉes ou รฉmotions refoulรฉes peuvent ressurgir sous d'autres formes et influencer notre comportement de maniรจre subtile.

Le dรฉni est un autre mรฉcanisme de dรฉfense courant. Il consiste ร refuser de reconnaรฎtre une rรฉalitรฉ qui nous est dรฉsagrรฉable ou menaรงante. Par exemple, une personne dรฉpendante ร l'alcool peut nier avoir un problรจme d'alcool et minimiser les consรฉquences de sa consommation.

Il est important de comprendre que ces mรฉcanismes de dรฉfense peuvent รชtre adaptatifs dans certaines situations. Ils nous aident ร faire face ร des รฉmotions ou des situations difficiles temporairement. Cependant, s'ils sont utilisรฉs de maniรจre excessive ou rigide, ils peuvent entraver notre croissance personnelle et nuire ร nos relations.

La prise de conscience de nos propres mรฉcanismes de dรฉfense est le premier pas vers un changement positif. En identifiant ces schรฉmas de comportement, nous pouvons commencer ร travailler sur une meilleure comprรฉhension de nous-mรชmes et sur des faรงons plus saines de faire face aux dรฉfis de la vie.

description:
The Dead Man's Fingers (Xylaria) is a Silver and Black Fungi of the Ascomycota Division! 
---
Identification: 
Accurate species identification requires genetic analysis (More Detail Info Under "Research Methods"). Feel free to comment any potential misidentifications.

Xylaria identification involves identifying its life cycle, which makes Xylaria collections difficult to identify. Various Xylaria species are distinguished by their sexual and asexual spores. Microscopic analysis is easier and more accurate to distinguish Xylaria species. Collectors tend to name their collections as โX. polymorphaโ or โX. hypoxylonโ because it's convenient for them.

title: Aluminum Skived fin Heat sink | Heatell
description:
Heatell Aluminum Skived fin Heat sink is a type of heat sink with fins that are produced by slicing or skiving thin sheets of aluminum. 
The fins are designed to increase the surface area of the heat sink, allowing it to dissipate heat more efficiently. 
These heatsinks are commonly used in electronic devices such as computers, servers, and LED lighting, to cool high-performance components such as CPUs, GPUs, and power regulators. 
The aluminum skived fin heat sinks are available in various sizes and shapes to meet the specific thermal management requirements of electronic devices. They are lightweight, durable, and have excellent thermal conductivity, making them an ideal choice for thermal management solutions in electronic devices.

title: How To clone A Hard Drive
description:
Here is how to clone a bootable windows hard drive. In this video are use a cloning device made by Sabrent that is very simple to use, and it copies everything from one hard drive to another hard drive. You can use one of these hard drive cloners to make a bootable copy of a Windows hard drive, so you take the hard drive out of a Windows computer and put it into the cloning device, and the cloning device makes a duplicate copy of the hard drive on a new drive, which you can use as a boot drive on your computer. When you put it in the computer, your computer will boot right up in windows with no problems. This Sabrent hard drive cloner device makes it very easy for people who want to upgrade their computer from a regular hard drive to an SSD drive so it will perform faster. โๆตทใฎใใใใโๆถๆปใฎๅฑๆฉใใ็ฐๅข็งป้ใ ใตใณใด็คๆใๆฅๆฌ็บใฎๆฐๆ่ก ใSDGsใ(2025ๅนด9ๆ26ๆฅ)ใใฌใๆๆฅใงใฏใๆชๆฅใใใใใใใใญใธใงใฏใใฎไธ็ฐใงSDGsไผ็ปใใไผใใใฆใใพใใ26ๆฅใฏใๆตทใฎ่ฑใใใๅฎใใใใงใใๆถๆปใฎๅฑๆฉใซใใใตใณใด็คใๆใๆฐใใชๆ่กใๆฅๆฌใง่ช็ใใพใใใ

ใๅๆใ็ฐๅข็ณปใใณใใฃใผไผๆฅญใชใฉใๅใใฆใๆซ้ฒ็ฎใใใฎใฏใ6ๆใซโๅฎคๅๆฐดๆงฝใฎไธญโใง่ช็ใใๆฅๆฌๅใฎใตใณใดใงใใ

ใใใใพใงใตใณใดใไบบๅทฅ็ใช็ฐๅขใง้ฃผ่ฒใใใฎใฏๅฐ้ฃใจใใใฆใใพใใใใโใใๆๆฐๆ่กโใซใใฃใฆ็ถๆณใๅคใใใพใใใ

ๆชๅผไผ็คพใคใใซใ้ซๅ่ๅคชไปฃ่กจ
ใๆฒ็ธใฎๆตทใซใใใใใซใตใณใดใซ้ฏ่ฆใใฆใใใฃใฆใ็ฃๅตใใใใใจใซๆๅใใพใใใ

title: Uma soluรงรฃo eficaz para controlar fungos e mofo em microverdes
description:
Os fungos e o mofo sรฃo problemas comuns enfrentados pelos produtores de microverdes. Esses microrganismos indesejados podem comprometer a qualidade e a seguranรงa dos produtos, alรฉm de reduzir o rendimento da colheita. Existem vรกrias razรตes pelas quais os microverdes sรฃo suscetรญveis ao crescimento de fungos e mofo, incluindo a alta umidade, a presenรงa de resรญduos orgรขnicos e as condiรงรตes ideais de temperatura para a proliferaรงรฃo desses micro-organismos.

Uma soluรงรฃo eficaz para controlar o crescimento de fungos e mofo nos microverdes รฉ o uso de inoculantes naturais, como bactรฉrias benรฉficas e fungos antagonistas, como as espรฉcies de Trichoderma. Esses inoculantes podem ser aplicados ao substrato durante o processo de cultivo ou pulverizados sobre as plantas durante o crescimento para competir com os organismos patogรชnicos e reduzir sua proliferaรงรฃo.

Ao incorporar inoculantes naturais em seus sistemas de cultivo de microverdes, os produtores podem reduzir a incidรชncia de fungos e mofo, aumentar a qualidade dos produtos e melhorar a saรบde geral do sistema de cultivo. No entanto, รฉ importante escolher os inoculantes corretos e seguir as instruรงรตes de aplicaรงรฃo para garantir resultados eficazes. Alรฉm disso, prรกticas culturais adequadas, como o controle da umidade e da ventilaรงรฃo, tambรฉm sรฃo essenciais para prevenir problemas de fungos e mofo nos microverdes.

Protocolos e processos, como o uso de inoculastes no substrato de cultivo, sรฃo as chaves para o sucesso da colheita dos microverdes. Comente QUERO APRENDER para receber uma mensagem sobre nossos treinamentos.

title: O que sรฃo FUNGOS? Desvendando o REINO FUNGI
description:
